# bad_url
# =======
# One Perl regular expression per line for URLs/domains found in article text.
# A hit normally contributes bad_url_score to the scoring engine; it is not by
# itself always an immediate rejection.  Do not write surrounding /.../ regex
# delimiters.
#
# Exact domain and every subdomain:
# (?:[a-z0-9-]+\.)*malware-domain\.example(?:/|$)
#
# Only one exact campaign path on a legitimate host:
# legitimate-host\.example/promo/campaign-4711(?:[/?#]|$)
#
# Generated tracking host with exactly twelve hexadecimal characters:
# click-[a-f0-9]{12}\.tracking-abuse\.example(?:/|$)
#
# Either HTTP or HTTPS is normally removed/handled by Cleanfeed before this
# expression is applied; match the host/path, not a hard-coded protocol unless
# a local test proves otherwise.
#
# Two related domains without duplicating the suffix:
# (?:drop-one|drop-two)\.bad-network\.example(?:/|$)
#
# Punycode/IDN host example (match the ASCII form seen in logs):
# xn--example-campaign-9db\.invalid(?:/|$)
#
# Avoid bare shorteners, public cloud/storage hosts, common TLDs, or broad
# expressions such as ".*download.*".  Shared services need path- or
# campaign-specific evidence.
